<h2> Timeline of Immigration Laws from 2017-2019 </h2>
<h5> Feburary 15, 2019 </h5>
<h6> Trump signs bill to fund parts of the government and border barrier; declares state of emergency </h6>
<p> President Donald Trump signed a $328 billion spending bill that included $1.375 billion in funding for barriers on the southern border. 
He had requested more for wall funding and because he did not receieve the amount requested, he declared a state of emergency on 
the southern border and directed $8.1 billion to build a border wall. Trump said, “It’s a great thing to do because we have an 
invasion of drugs, invasion of gangs, invasion of people.” His actions have been criticed by House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Senate 
Minority Leader Chuch Schumer, saying, "The president's unlawful declaration over a rissi that does not exsist does great violence 
to our Constitution and makes America less safe. The president is not above the law. The Congress cannot let the president shred 
the Constitution." </p>
<h5> February 3, 2019 </h5>
<h6> Trump administration announces more troops headed to southern border </h6> 
<p>The U.S. Department of Defense announced that 3,700 members of the military would be sent to the southern border. They were sent 
there to assist Customs and Border Protection. Before the deployment, there were nearly 650 troops at the border.President Trump 
innitially wanted to send troops to the board on April 4, 2018 Trump says that they were deployed to stop "a drastic surge of 
illegal activity on the southern border." </p>
<h5> January 19, 2019 </h5>
<h6> Trump releases plan to secure border and end partial shutdown </h6>
<p> President Trump created a plan to secure the southern boarder and end the government's partial shutdown 
<br> Trump's plain included: 
<ul> 
<li> $5.7 billion to fund a steel barrier system </li>
<li> $805 million for technology, canines, and personnel to prevent drugs and weapons from being brought into the country </li>
<li> $800 million dollars in humanitarian assistance, medical support, and new temporary housing </li>
<li> $782 million to hire an additional 2,750 border agents, law enforcement officers, and staff </li>
<li> $563 million for the immigration court system, including hiring 75 new immigration judge teams </li>
<li> Three years of provisional status for DACA and certain Temporary Protected Status (TPS) recipients, which would protect them 
from deportation. </li> 
</ul>
<h5> January 8, 2019 </h5>
<h6> Democratic Leaders reject Trump's border barrier address </h6>
<p> In a televised address on January 8, 2019,President Trump President said there was a crisis the southern boarder and wanted 
Congress to give $5.7 billion to build a wall or steel barrier. He said, “At the request of Democrats, it will be a steel barrier 
rather than a concrete wall. This barrier is absolutely critical to border security. It’s also what our professionals at the border
want and need.” </p>
<h5> December 21, 2018 </h5>
<h6> Trump shut downs the government for border wall funding </h6>
<p> The government shut down was in response to funding for the border wall not included in a continuing resolution (CR) to fund 
the government. On December 21, 2018, President Trump made the address announcing that there would be a government shut down until 
he gets funding for the border wall. After, $5 billion was passed for funding for a border wall.</p>
<h5> October 30, 2018 </h5>
<h6> Trump proposes ending birthright citizenship </h6>
<p> President Trump said in an inter view that he would sign an executive order ending birthright citizenship to children of 
noncitizens. Trump said, "We're the only country in the world where a person comes in and has a baby, and the baby is essentially a 
citizen of the United States ... with all of those benefits. It's ridiculous. It's ridiculous." </p>
<h6> Trump administration to send troops to U.S.-Mexico border </h6>
<h5> June 20, 2018 </h5> 
<h6> Trump signs an executive order addressing the separation of children from parents crossing the border illegally </h6>
<p> President Trump signed an executive order to keep immigrating detained families together. Another part of it is that the U.S. 
Department of Defense had to assist in finding the families housing when detention centers are full. On May 7, 2018, the paretns 
would be seperated from their chidlren until there was a result to their case. Trump said, "We’re going to keep families together 
but we still have to maintain toughness or our country will be overrun by people, by crime, by all of the things that we don’t 
stand for and that we don’t want." </p>
<h5> June 11, 2018 </h5>
<h6> Sessions says individuals who are victims of private crime not eligible for asylum </h6>
<p> On June 11, 2018, Attorney General Jeff Sessions announced that people who are victims of personal crime are not elegable for 
asylum in the United States. U. S. Sessions said, "Our nation’s immigration laws provide for asylum to be granted to individuals 
who have been persecuted, or who have a well-founded fear of persecution, on account of their membership in a ‘particular social 
group,’ but most victims of personal crimes do not fit this definition—no matter how vile and reprehensible the crime perpetrated 
against them." </p>
<h5> May 1, 2018 </h5>  
<h6> Texas and six other states file lawsuit to end DACA </h6>
<P On May 1, 2018, Texas and six other states filed a lawsuit because they believed that the continuation of the DACA program was 
unlawful. They argued that the program required them to spend more money on healthcare, law enforcement, and education. Also, the 
program increased competition for jobs. </p>
<h5> April 24, 2018 </h5> 
<h6> Judge rules Trump administration must continue accepting new DACA applications </h6>
<h5> March 6, 2018 </h5> 
<h6> DOJ files lawsuit against California's immigration laws </h6>
<h5> February 26, 2018 </h5> 
<h6> SCOTUS denies Trump administration's request to review DACA case </h6>
<h5> February 15, 2018 </h5> 
<h6> Senate rejects four immigration reform proposals </h6>
<h5> January 25, 2018 </h5>
<h6> Trump administration releases initial framework for immigration plan </h6>
<h5> January 24, 2018 </h5> 
<h6> Trump says he supports a pathway to citizenship for DACA recipients </h6>
<h5> January 9, 2018 <h5>  
<h6> Judge rules that Trump administration must keep renewing DACA permits </h6>
<h5> January 8, 2018 </h5> 
<h6> DHS announces end date for program allowing El Salvadorans to live and work in U.S. </h6>
